MACHINE LEARNING - INDIVIDUAL PROJECT¶

DESCRIPTON¶

This dataset is composed of 1400 samples with 20 features each. The first column is the sample id. The second column in the dataset represents the label. There are 3 possible values for the labels. The remaining columns are numeric features.

Your task is the following: assuming that you want to classify this data with Logistic Regression (implemented by sklearn.linear_model.LogisticRegression), you should determine whether applying PCA to this dataset is useful, and if so what number of components you would choose to use. At the end of the analysis, you should have chosen an optimal strategy, including the optimal set of parameters for the classifier: write this choice explicitly in the conclusions of your notebook.

Your notebook should detail the procedure you have used to choose the optimal parameters (graphs are a good idea when possible/sensible).

The notebook will be evaluated not only based on the final results, but also on the procedure employed, which should balance practical considerations (one may not be able to exhaustively explore all possible combinations of the parameters) with the desire for achieving the best possible performance in the least amount of time.

Bonus points may be assigned for particularly clean/nifty code and/or well- presented results.

You are also free to attempt other strategies beyond the one in the assignment (which however is mandatory!).

As the previous plots suggest, we proceed by standardizing our features, that is subctraing the mean and dividing by the standard deviation. We proceed splitting our data set (both features and labels) in train and test and then scaling the train and test features since are the ones that we are going to use in our classification. In this way our datset is splitted in a random way having 80% of the samples for training and the remaining 20% for testing

PCA¶

The nex part of our data anlysis is about performing a PCA in order to reduce dimensionality and see if it is useful in order to classify our data. The previous plot about correlation of our features make us doubt about its usefulness but we will proceed seeing if it can increase the accuracy of our classifier

In [219]:
def run_PCA(df1, df2, n_components, plot1 = False, plot2 = False):

    X = df1.to_numpy()
    Y = df2.to_numpy()

    # this first paragrapgh of code is about seeing the cumulative variance and the importance of each component in the case we take all the features
    if n_components == 20:
        pca = PCA(n_components = n_components)
        X_train_pca = pca.fit_transform(X)
        X_test_pca = pca.transform(Y)
        print('Original shape:', X.shape)
        print('Original shape:', Y.shape)
        explained_variance = pca.explained_variance_ratio_
        cumulative_variance = np.cumsum(explained_variance)
        for i in range(1,20):
            print(f'Cumulative variance for component {i + 1}: {cumulative_variance[i]}')
    
    else:
        pca = PCA(n_components = n_components)
        X_train_pca = pca.fit_transform(X)
        X_test_pca = pca.transform(Y)
        print('Reduced shape:', X_train_pca.shape)
        print('Reduced shape:', X_test_pca.shape)
        explained_variance = pca.explained_variance_ratio_
        cumulative_variance = np.cumsum(explained_variance)
        print('Explained variance per component:', explained_variance)
        print('Total explained variance:', sum(explained_variance))


    if plot1:    
        var = pca.explained_variance_ratio_[0:n_components]
        labels = ["PC"+str(i+1) for i in range(n_components)]
        plt.figure(figsize=(15,4))
        plt.bar(labels, var)
        plt.xlabel('Pricipal Components')
        plt.ylabel('Proportion of Variance Explained')
        plt.show()

    if plot2:
        fig = plt.figure(figsize=(18,10))
        
        plt.subplot(2, 2, 1)
        var = pca.explained_variance_ratio_[0:n_components]
        labels = ["PC"+str(i+1) for i in range(n_components)]
        #plt.figure(figsize=(12,4))
        plt.bar(labels, var)
        plt.xlabel('Pricipal Components')
        plt.ylabel('Proportion of Variance Explained')
        
        plt.subplot(2, 2, 2)
        #cumulative_explained_variance = np.cumsum(explained_variance)
        plt.plot(range(1, len(cumulative_variance) + 1), cumulative_variance, marker='o')
        #plt.axhline(y=0.95, color='grey', linestyle='--')
        #plt.text(1.1, 1, '95% cut-off threshold', color = 'black', fontsize=16)
        plt.xlabel('Number of Components')
        plt.ylabel('Cumulative Explained Variance')
        plt.title('PCA Explained Variance')
        plt.grid()
        
        plt.show()
    
    

    return X_train_pca, X_test_pca

First of all we analyze the PCA applied in the maximum number of components (that is all the features, 20) in order to see the cumulative variance expressed by each component and their importance

The cumulative variance explained by the principal components in PCA provides insight into how much of the total variance in the dataset is captured as more components are included. Indeed, we got interesting results:

  • Only using the first 3 components, we almost reach 30% of variance explained
  • Using 15 components, we have more than 95% of variance explained
  • No additional variance is captured with more than 18 components

LOGISTIC REGRESSION¶

We now start building our classifier, the Logistic Regression. We will perform it starting with default parameters (apart from the multiclass, since the class of our labels is 3, and solvers that do not conflict with the respective penalty) and then we will Hyper-tune the parameters.

In [224]:
Y = '\033[93m'
E = '\033[0m'

def run_logistic(X, y):
    model = LogisticRegressionCV(random_state=42, multi_class= 'multinomial', cv =5 , max_iter=50000)
    model.fit(X, y)

    logistic_regression_l1 = LogisticRegressionCV( penalty = 'l1', solver= 'saga' , cv = 5, random_state= 42, multi_class= 'multinomial', max_iter=50000)
    logistic_regression_l1.fit(X, y)

    logistic_regression_l2 = LogisticRegressionCV( penalty = 'l2', solver= 'saga' , cv = 5, random_state= 42, multi_class= 'multinomial', max_iter=50000)
    logistic_regression_l2.fit(X, y)

    logistic_regression_el = LogisticRegressionCV( penalty = 'elasticnet', solver= 'saga' , cv = 5, random_state= 42, multi_class= 'multinomial', l1_ratios = [0.2,0.5,0.8], max_iter=50000)
    logistic_regression_el.fit(X, y)

    return model, logistic_regression_l1, logistic_regression_l2, logistic_regression_el

Let's now try to fine-tune our classifier.

Differently from what we did in the Original Dataset, here using GridSearch to find best combination of Logistic Regression parameter is not enough, (more precisely it will not be accurate). The best way to proceed is to use a Pipeline in order to choose the optimal combination of Logistic parameters considering also the choice of number of components for the PCA.

RANDOM FOREST (EXTRA)¶

Why Random Forest?¶

I chose Random Forest as another classifier in order to perform a features selection. After performing Random Forest I will select the most important features according to this classifier and use them to perform again Logistic Regression. In this way at the end of the analysis I will compare the results and performances of Logistic Regression obtained by the three different strategies that I have used:

  • Logistic Regression on the raw dataset (Scaling X_train and X_test)
  • Logistic Regression using data obtained by the PCA (X_train_pca, X_test_pca)
  • Logistic Regression using data obtained by features selection of Random Forest

Classification¶

We start building our classifier both on the Original Dataset (X_train standardize) and on the Dataset reduced with PCA (X_train standardize obtained by dimensionality reduction), in order to see in which dataset the model perform in a better way

CONCLUSION¶

Overall, the different types of Logistic Regression that I have performed give very similar results. The cross-validation score of the best models chosen (through GridSearch, regarding Orignal Dataset and the one using most important features selected by Random Forest, through GridSearch and the use of the pipeline regarding the Dataset reduced with PCA) are almost the same. As far as the performance metrics are concerned, the ones of the Original Dataset are slightly better. For this reason the final model that I decided to choose in order to make prediction is the Logistic Regression performed on the Orginal Dataset (after being improved using hyperparameters) with the following parameters:
